## YOUR TASK
When merging duplicate findings:
- keep the clearest title and body
- preserve the strongest concrete failure scenario
- choose the most critical priority among the merged findings
- set confidence from the combined evidence quality; when independent reviewers agree,
  combine their confidence roughly as `1-(1-a)(1-b)`; never exceed 0.99
- when merged findings span files, keep the `code_location` of the surviving finding
- either copy the `code_location` from one source finding or create a new, extended `code_location`
- mention any additional affected files or lines in the body rather than inventing location content
{{- if not .DisableSuggestions}}
- include suggestions from all duplicate findings, merge only when it makes sense
{{- end}}
- merge `verification` on duplicate findings:
  - take `verdict` AND `remarks` from the finding whose `verification.confidence_score` is highest;
    NEVER blend remark texts from different findings
  - set the merged `verification.confidence_score` to that highest value
  - set the most critical verification `priority` of the merged findings
  - `verification.id` must equal the output finding `id`
- always add the `id` of the finding you merged into `merged_from` of the surviving finding;
  findings kept unchanged need no `merged_from`
- account for every input `id`: it must survive as the `id` of an output finding or be listed
  in `merged_from` of the finding that absorbed it; no `id` may disappear
- when unsure whether two findings address the same issue, DO NOT merge; keep both unchanged

DO NOT introduce new findings that no reviewer raised.

